===Etymology===
From {{etyl|xno|en}} {{term|buisart|lang=fro}}, from {{etyl|fro|en}} {{term|buison|lang=fro}}, {{term|buson|lang=fro}} (French {{term|buse|lang=fr}}), possibly from {{etyl|la|en}} {{term|buteon|buteōn|[[buteo]]|lang=la}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|/ˈbʌzəɻd/}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# Any of several [[Old-World]] [[bird of prey|birds of prey]] with broad wings and a broad tail.
# In North America, a general term for scavenging birds such as the [[American black vulture]], also called [[American black buzzard]] (''[[Coragyps atratus]]''), and the [[turkey vulture]] (''[[Cathartes aura]]'').
# {{context|colloquial|often preceded by "old"|lang=en}} a [[curmudgeonly]] or [[cantankerous]] man.
# {{context|archaic|lang=en}} A [[blockhead]]; a [[dunce]].
#* Goldsmith
#*: It is common, to a proverb, to call one who can not be taught, or who continues obstinately ignorant, '''a buzzard'''.

